Sure, here is a sample SAS program to open a text file and flag duplicate records:

```SAS
libname mydata 'C:\Data'; /* declaring the library to read the input data */

data mydata.my_input_file; /* creating a SAS dataset from the text file */
  infile 'C:\Data\my_input_file.txt'; /* input file path */
  input record $100.; /* assuming each record has a maximum length of 100 characters */
run;

proc sort data=mydata.my_input_file nodupkey out=mydata.my_deduplicated_file; /* sorting the data and removing duplicates */
  by record;
run;

data mydata.my_flagged_file; /* creating a new dataset to flag duplicate records */
  set mydata.my_input_file; /* reading the original dataset */
  if _n_=1 then do; /* initializing a counter for each record */
    counter=1;
  end;
  else if record=lag(record) then do; /* comparing the current record with the previous record */
    counter+1;
    duplicate='Y'; /* flagging the record as a duplicate */
  end;
  else do;
    counter+1;
    duplicate='N'; /* flagging the record as not a duplicate */
  end;
run;
```

This program assumes that the input text file is located in the "C:\Data" directory. You should modify the file path to match the actual location of your input file. The program will first create a SAS dataset from the text file, then sort the data and remove duplicate records using the "nodupkey" option of the SORT procedure. Finally, the program will create a new dataset to flag duplicate records by comparing each record with the previous record and incrementing a counter for each record. The flag will be set to "Y" for duplicate records and "N" for non-duplicate records.
